WEBVTT

00:01.413 --> 00:03.695
I have... Alzheimer's.

00:05.960 --> 00:07.852
I found this in your desk.

00:09.769 --> 00:10.982
"To Dad."

00:11.830 --> 00:15.113
"I am taking Mom someplace better."

00:15.650 --> 00:18.091
"So you can never
make her feel bad again."

00:19.375 --> 00:20.853
Jesus Christ!

00:21.030 --> 00:23.157
You're the head guy on that panel.
Advised the government.

00:23.241 --> 00:26.452
Told them that genetically modified fish
were safe for human consumption.

00:26.536 --> 00:27.998
That's my boy, Dr. Sandstrom.

00:28.196 --> 00:31.203
One day he's running in the yard.
Next day, his whole body's paralyzed.

00:31.361 --> 00:33.666
Basically we found a group of kids
with muscle development problems.

00:33.755 --> 00:36.630
We're looking into
their family histories... DNA samples.

00:36.834 --> 00:40.065
Bob, are you saying that
something was dumped there?

00:40.956 --> 00:42.471
It wasn't an accident.

00:42.658 --> 00:45.822
An accident implies I made a mistake,
and I did not make a mistake.

00:45.997 --> 00:49.042
I need you to sign these forms
that NorBAC is not legally responsible.

00:49.168 --> 00:50.682
Tell you what,
I'll sign those papers

00:50.765 --> 00:52.523
as soon as you start
doing your job around here.

00:52.747 --> 00:54.433
- And what is that supposed to mean?
- That means:

00:54.548 --> 00:56.180
figure out why
things are going missing.

00:56.335 --> 00:58.650
Find out who's fucking around
with my lab equipment.

00:58.738 --> 01:00.741
A National Guard unit in Canton, Ohio

01:00.878 --> 01:04.569
was doing a routine endurance course.
These are troops ramping up for Iraq.

01:04.797 --> 01:05.871
Excellent condition.

01:06.668 --> 01:08.742
They all came down
with the same symptoms.

01:08.906 --> 01:12.293
Headaches, flu-like symptom,
blurred vision, severe muscle pain.

01:12.448 --> 01:13.740
And then there was the psychosis.

01:14.058 --> 01:15.903
Sleepiness, right?

01:16.427 --> 01:19.031
- Okay.
- Sleepiness into coma.

01:21.277 --> 01:24.052
- Encephalitis Lethargica?
- Highly contagious,

01:24.208 --> 01:27.053
over 5 million people got it,
no one ever figured it out.

01:28.897 --> 01:31.473
Yes, Sir.
I'll put a note on his desk.

01:31.985 --> 01:35.202
Connor McGuinn's office.
I'm sorry, he's in a meeting.

01:35.485 --> 01:37.463
I'll make sure he gets the message.

01:38.278 --> 01:39.940
Thank you for holding.

01:40.097 --> 01:42.941
I'm sorry,
Captain McGuinn is out of the office.

01:43.207 --> 01:44.613
Of course.

01:45.777 --> 01:47.351
Connor McGuinn's office.

01:47.535 --> 01:50.443
Yes, Ms. Morrison,
I'll put you right through.

01:52.708 --> 01:53.990
Connor McGuinn's office.

01:54.188 --> 01:56.410
... then you're sure
it's Encephalitis Lethargica?

01:56.558 --> 01:59.942
Jill and I went back to Ohio yesterday
to double check the symptomology.

02:00.126 --> 02:01.960
All the Guardsmen have it: fever.

02:02.166 --> 02:05.132
You know, they can barely
stay awake. Hallucinations.

02:05.217 --> 02:07.762
It's progressing exactly like Lethargica.

02:08.038 --> 02:09.353
<i>And the prognosis?</i>

02:09.616 --> 02:12.641
Everything I've read,
anything from psychosis to death.

02:12.925 --> 02:16.443
Two million people died
during the last outbreak in the 20's.

02:16.757 --> 02:18.901
So, we're looking at
a highly contagious virus?

02:19.037 --> 02:21.811
Depends on the strain.
Which we haven't figured out yet.

02:21.906 --> 02:24.380
Connor, if there is another outbreak,

02:24.837 --> 02:26.982
it could kill millions again.

02:27.198 --> 02:28.992
Well, how did we stop
it back in the twenties?

02:29.256 --> 02:30.791
We didn't. We got lucky.

02:30.946 --> 02:34.450
Except for a few isolated cases,
it just vectored out and disappeared.

02:34.535 --> 02:36.770
And now it just
suddenly comes back?

02:36.945 --> 02:38.223
It's a retrovirus!

02:38.337 --> 02:41.331
It's something we all have
sleeping in our DNA.

02:42.577 --> 02:44.050
Is it possible...

02:45.646 --> 02:47.681
Could Al-Qaeda have
the means to wake it up?

02:47.926 --> 02:49.560
There's a lot of
dirty scientists out there

02:49.716 --> 02:52.140
who'd be willing to make
a few extra bucks to help them out.

02:52.358 --> 02:54.143
<i>Captain, Dr. Henshaw is on "two".</i>

02:55.446 --> 02:56.583
Thank you.

02:57.347 --> 03:00.430
Doctor, I'm conferencing you with
David Sandstrom and Caroline Morrison.

03:00.646 --> 03:03.803
Good. Good.
Dr. Sandstrom, can you hear me?

03:03.948 --> 03:06.860
Yeah, fine. How'd
the Guardsmen react to the Levodopa?

03:07.325 --> 03:10.042
Good idea you had there,
Doctor, but no...

03:10.288 --> 03:12.411
- No effect.
- Not at all?

03:12.565 --> 03:14.451
We even pushed
the dosage to the limit.

03:14.535 --> 03:16.581
Levodopa should have
gone right to the symptoms.

03:16.736 --> 03:19.670
Then you could be wrong?
Maybe we're not dealing with Lethargica.

03:19.828 --> 03:22.391
- We need you right now.
- You know what, Doctor? I've got to go.

03:22.605 --> 03:24.453
No, it's gotta be Lethargica.

03:24.717 --> 03:26.843
Maybe we're looking
at a different strain,

03:26.927 --> 03:30.023
<i>- or maybe it's been altered to resist Levodopa.
- Altered?</i>

03:30.515 --> 03:33.300
- You mean weaponized?
- It'd make the perfect weapon.

03:33.637 --> 03:36.783
Something we've ignored
for the better part of a century.

03:38.638 --> 03:41.732
Something
we haven't got a clue how to fight.

